desc=Scouts specialize in stealth operations in the wilderness. They are similar to Rangers in some ways, having similar functions and abilities. Scouts have the same attack bonus and saving throws as Thieves of the same level. They have been toughened by self-sufficiency and isolation from the supplies and comforts of civilized lands, and therefore use a d6 for hit dice. It also takes more training to be a Scout, and therefore Scouts advance at the same rate as Clerics. Scouts should be treated as Thieves for all purposes, except as described herein.//To become a Scout, a character must have both a Wisdom and Dexterity score of 9 or higher. As with the Thief, a Scout may not wear metal armor, nor may they use shields of any sort. They may use any weapon. Any race may be a Scout.//Scouts are able to detect traps at an improved rate (`!trap`), but unlike Thieves they do not have the ability to remove them. However, their ability to detect traps applies equally well to snares and pits in the wilderness as well as the more common form of dungeon or fortress traps.//Unlike a Thief, a Scout gains no special bonuses for making sneak attacks in melee, though normal bonuses for attacking from behind or with surprise are applied.//Scouts are always experts at ranged weapons. When using any ranged weapon, a Scout adds +1 to all attack rolls, and may ``snipe`` to do double damage if attacking an opponent unawares (determined by the GM). At 9th level a Scout's ability with ranged weapons becomes so great that he or she no longer suffers a penalty for attacking at long range.

